President Reagan has made welfare reform a priority.  His Domestic
Policy Council drafted a blueprint giving states wider latitude to
experiment with reform.  Many governors have unveiled plans of their
own.

A welfare lobbying coalition of 80 organizations has issued a
statement calling for increased spending for poverty and jobs
programs.  They insist that the federal government has "primary
responsibility" for welfare.  Congressional Democrats seem to agree
with them.  Americans are already spending more than $100 billion a
year on welfare.  It may be necessary for Reagan to form an alliance
of reform-minded governors and the public to change the status
quo.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d12"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ870227-0149"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="B"> 
 
The National Governors Association presented a welfare reform plan to
President Reagan that would require welfare recipients to do something
productive to earn their benefits, be it completing school, receiving
vocational training or holding a job.  The governors' proposal will
cost $2 billion per year in addition to the $100 billion now spent on
poverty programs.  Reagan doesn't like their plan's national minimum
benefit level, which he believes will undercut each states' ability to
set its own standard.  Several states have already launched successful
work-for-welfare programs, thus encouraging many other states to try
something similar. Reform consensus seems to be building.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d12"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ871215-0109"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="B">
 
The goal of welfare reform should be: to shrink the welfare system, to
eliminate perverse incentives to remain on welfare, and to make work
the focus of reform.  Many believe the House of Representative's
Family Welfare Reform Act of 1987 fails to do that.  It proposes $5.2
billion in new spending over five years, most to expand existing
welfare programs.  Proponents say the new money is an investment, that
some money will go to new programs to induce welfare recipients off
the rolls and into jobs.  Detractors say it amounts to an expanded
investment in the status quo.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d12"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880903-0092"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="B">
 
A House-Senate conference committee has before it two welfare reform
bills --- the Senate-passed bill containing a work requirement, the
House-approved measure without.  President Reagan stated that
unemployment was near a 14-year low.  He would veto any welfare
legislation not containing a work requirement.

Rep. Thomas J. Downey, D-N.Y., states that 32.5 million Americans
remain mired in poverty.  He feels that state and local, not federal,
welfare officials should control any welfare work requirement.  He
believes that the House bill, with training and education programs,
and health and child-care benefits, would make welfare parents who
work better off than those who don't.</SUM>

<SUM
