SUMMARIZER="B">
     
President Clinton states that he is committed to "ending welfare as we
know it."  He will base his reforms on the principle that welfare
should not be a way of life.  His reform will focus on better
implementation of the Family Support Act, a 1988 welfare reform based
on NGA task-force work that he, as governor of Arkansas, co-chaired.
However, with the onset of recession, states' revenues are constrained
while the number of welfare recipients has increased.  Therefore, few
states are able to implement the Act's requirements for education or
training.  Clinton will allow states to experiment with their own
reforms.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d12"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT933-6011"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="B">
 
Clinton campaigned on welfare reform.  But, as president, he is first
addressing two higher priorities: deficit reduction and healthcare
reform, both of which, he believes, will help alleviate welfare.  He
has improved the earned income tax credit and will enforce laws
requiring financial support from absentee fathers.  These measures may
help but will not solve America's welfare problems.  Many
conservatives favor a strict time limit, two years, for welfare.  Most
people consider this too drastic.  Something like an FDR public sector
works program, although probably not affordable, might work.  Many
think the bipartisan Family Support Act of 1988 is the answer.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d12"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT934-12800"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="B">
          
Fundamental welfare reform is needed within the 24 member nations of
the Organization for Economic Co-operation if these states are to
protect their most vulnerable citizens without endangering their
economies.  Welfare costs, principally for pensions, healthcare,
unemployment benefits and family support are rapidly becoming
insupportable.  The costliest item is pensions, which continue to grow
due to increased coverage, benefit levels and an aging population.  By
the year 2040, people over age 65 will rise from their current 19% of
total population to 37%.  In a competitive global economy, no country
can burden its businesses with higher welfare costs than its
neighbors.</SUM>

<SUM
